\begin{abstract}
This paper derives Standard Model lepton and quark rest masses from the 600-cell lattice geometry, using first-principles calculations of SSV binding energies without experimental calibration. SSV₀ is derived from Planck scales and lattice parameters. Shell radii are computed from actual 600-cell vertex coordinates, with binding energies as discrete sums over 1/r gradients (justified as lattice approximation to continuous potentials). We provide complete step-by-step derivations for the muon (tetrahedral cage) and charm quark (icosahedral), predicting masses and comparing to observed values (accepting initial discrepancies for refinement in later papers). Neutrino masses are explained as residual vibrations. The framework demonstrates geometric origins for mass hierarchies, with predictions achieving reasonable order-of-magnitude agreement as an initial approximation.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Paper 1 derived SSV gradient force laws and binding energies for cage configurations. This paper extends to mass generation: rest masses emerge from cumulative binding energy across successive cage layers, derived solely from lattice geometry and fundamental constants. We eliminate calibration by deriving SSV₀ from Planck scales, justify 1/r potentials as discrete approximations, and use simulated lattice distances for shell radii. Predictions are made ab initio, with initial errors discussed for future refinements (e.g., relativistic effects in Paper 5).

\section{Derivation of SSV₀ from First Principles}

The elementary SSV magnitude SSV₀ is derived from the Planck energy E_P = √(ℏ c^5 / G) ≈ 1.956 × 10^9 J, divided by the lattice's degrees of freedom N_lattice ≈ 120 (number of vertices, scaled by φ ≈ 1.618 for symmetry factor):

\begin{equation}
\text{SSV}_0 = \frac{E_P}{N_lattice \cdot \phi} \approx \frac{1.956 \times 10^9 \, \text{J}}{120 \cdot 1.618} \approx 1.007 \times 10^7 \, \text{J} \approx 6.28 \times 10^{15} \, \text{MeV}
\end{equation}

This reflects SSV as energy density at the Planck scale, distributed across the finite lattice. Physical masses will be predicted using this value.

\section{Layered Binding Accumulation}

Total rest energy (predicted mass m c^2 = E_total):

\begin{equation}
E_{\text{total}} = \sum_{k=0}^{N} E_{\text{binding},k}
\label{eq:total_binding}
\end{equation}

Per-layer binding (discrete sum over shell CPs at distances r_i from center):

\begin{equation}
E_{\text{binding},k} = \sum_{i \in \text{shell}_k} \frac{\text{SSV}_0 \cdot p_i \cdot t_i}{r_i}
\label{eq:layer_binding}
\end{equation}

\section{Justification of 1/r Potential from Discrete Lattice}

In continuous space, 1/r² field gives 1/r potential. In the discrete 600-cell, SSV attenuates as 1/r² per hop, but the potential is the cumulative sum along paths: For a chain of N hops with average hop length d_hop, Φ ≈ ∑ (SSV₀ / (m d_hop)^2) * m d_hop ≈ SSV₀ ln(N) / d_hop ≈ SSV₀ / r for large N (harmonic approximation to integral). This justifies 1/r as the effective potential for bindings.

\section{Shell Radii from Lattice Geometry}

Using 600-cell vertex coordinates (normalized to unit sphere), unique distances from a reference vertex: 0.618 (φ^{-1}), 1.0, 1.176 (φ - 0.618), 1.414 (√2), 1.618 (φ), 1.732 (√3), 1.902 (φ + 0.618), 2.0.

Assign shells:
- Tetrahedral (shortest: average r_1 = 0.618)
- Icosahedral (next: r_2 = 1.0)
- Dodecahedral (r_3 = 1.176)
- Fullerene (higher average r_4 ≈ 1.618)

Scale by lattice constant d_0 = l_P (Planck length) for physical units, but keep normalized for predictions.

